    <title>Combined summary - Speedy covenants (OP_CAT2)</title>
    <updated>2023-06-15T20:37:03.519525+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2022-May/020429.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Bitcoin-dev mailing list has been discussing the implementation of covenants and the potential re-enabling of OP_CAT. Although OP_CAT alone does not enable covenants, it can create recursive covenants when combined with other covenant opcodes. The discussion also covers the possibility of creating negative fee transactions, as well as the use of TapScript and the risks associated with using OP_EVAL for covenants. There are debates over which proposal is best, with some favoring simplicity while others prefer speedy covenants or a new scripting language. It is suggested that any proposal will require careful consideration of factors such as efficiency, ease of validation, and safety. While non-recursive covenants can be enabled with OP_CAT, enabling recursive covenants is still uncertain.In an email exchange on May 13, 2022, Anthony Towns discussed the factors to consider when proposing a specific opcode. These factors include how much can be done with it, how efficient it is to validate, how easy it is to make it do what is intended, how helpful it is at preventing bugs, and how clean and maintainable the validation code is. Towns then provided his opinion on various proposals, stating that CTV and APO are weakest in terms of what can be done with them, while CAT/CSFS fails in ease of use and bug prevention. Towns suggested that the primary purpose of the proposal for CAT+CSFS would be to validate oracle messages and pubkey delegation, with covenants serving as a secondary function to gather data on user preferences.Bitcoin Script opcodes, such as OP_SUBSTR or OP_SPLIT, can be used instead of OP_CAT to enable quining and implement recursive covenants. However, the safety of recursive covenants must be ensured before enabling them. There have been discussions on the benefits and risks of implementing covenants, and various approaches have been proposed. The removal of OP_CAT was not solely due to its association with covenants but also because of its potential to cause memory issues. Covenants were first discussed during P2SH discussions aimed at solving the problem of k-of-n multisignature. The use of OP_EVAL and P2SH created a separate script containing public keys and hashed it, with the hash included in the scriptPubKey.The proposal for speedy covenants has been implemented for the longest time and is simpler than other proposals, while the simplicity proposal introduces a complete new scripting language that is better in many senses. The decision of whether and how to implement covenants will require careful consideration of various factors. Regarding specific opcode proposals, it is suggested to consider how much can be done with it, how efficient it is to validate, how easy it is to make it do what you want, how helpful it is at preventing bugs, and how clean and maintainable the validation code is.Recursive covenants are close to true Turing-completeness, which creates a risk of denial-of-service attacks on the network. However, non-recursive covenants can be enabled with OP_CTV and SIGHASH_ANYPREVOUT. The safety of covenants depends on how addresses are generated, and fears of forced forward-encumbrance are not any worse than what can be done today. There were concerns about the use of TapScript and the possibility of re-enabling OP_CAT in a soft-forked manner. There were also proposals for speedy covenants or OP_CAT2, which was considered simpler but still carried some risks. Another proposal called the simplicity proposal introduces a complete new scripting language that is better in many senses but harder to review and test than other proposals. Overall, there are arguments both for and against deploying speedy covenants and the simplicity proposal in Bitcoin.To validate current opcodes and develop new ones, it is necessary to prove that they are not an undue burden on nodes in terms of validate-cpu-cycles-per-byte, and they won't introduce DDOS attack vectors. The burden of proof-of-safety is on the proposer, and if there is proof that total-with-codata is safe, opcodes that may enable recursive covenants can be added, and OP_CAT can be added back too.</summary>
